Stash 2.1 replaced the jTDS JDBC driver with Microsoft's own, for accessing SQL Server. Microsoft's JDBC URL allows for the following layout:
{noformat}
jdbc:sqlserver://hostname\instanceName:port;databaseName=database;
{noformat}

When using Stash's in-app screens for configuring a database, "hostname\instanceName" can be put into the hostname text box. Migration will complete successfully, and the system will connect to the desired instance.

However, when the JDBC URL is written into {{stash-config.properties}}, the \ between the hostname and instance name is not escaped (since the system does not actually support this usage). As a result, the first time the server is restarted the value becomes "hostnameinstanceName", because the \ is stripped as an invalid escape, and the database connection fails.

Instead of asking customers to change the {{server.xml}} we should look into making those settings ({{port}}, {{contextPath}} come to mind) overridable so that they can be changed without having to change any files.

E.g. to change the port you could use:

{code}
./bin/start-stash.sh --port=8090
{code}

If pull request can't be merged, Stash show instructions how to solve this and this instructions are wrong:
{quote}
Merge conflict
This merge has conflicts. You must resolve the conflicts before merging the pull request:
Step 1: Fetch the changes and checkout the destination branch.
{code}
git fetch 
git checkout master
{code}
Step 2: Merge the source branch and resolve conflicts as appropriate.
{code}
git merge -m "Merge pull request #4 from feature-branch to master" --log --no-ff feature-branch
{code}
Step 3: After the merge conflicts are resolved, commit the changes and push.
{code}
git commit 
git push origin HEAD
{code}
{quote}

First off all. You must merge master into feature-branch, but not a feature-branch to master. You should make Pull Request is valid to merge via button in web interface. Not a merge with bypass it.

The permissions to push changes into master is only on some lead developers. If all start to resolve conflict, this make them very unhapy. Only author of feature-branch must merge conflicts, but author has no access to push into master.

You should done resolve conflicts by this commands:
{code}
git fetch
git checkout feature-branch
git merge --no-ff master
git push origin feature-branch
{code}

This make opened Pull Request available to merge from web interface.

{noformat}
TypeError: opt_data.project is undefined
{noformat}

This is caused due to the fact that {{stash.feature.project.projectRow}} (in projectTable.soy) was changed to take a project as a parameter instead as the data itself.

*Workaround*: Navigate to the repositories via the per project repository list (.e.g https://stash.example.com/projects/PROJECT_KEY) or via the "Recently Viewed" repository list in the menu.

